<Author>willbegone
<Content>Not up to Hilton Standards I stayed at this hotel while on a business trip. Overall, my comment is that for the price, this hotel is not a great value. I鈥檝e itemized the pluses and minues at the bottom of this review. The price you pay will greatly influence your satisfaction rating. My corporate rate is $145/night which is similar to the rate you can get directly from Hilton if you are willing to prepay your stay at time of reservation without refund. I would not recommend that so as to allow you to checkout if you are disappointed after the first night. You will definitely be happy with this hotel should you be able to snag a room for $100/night (a rate I've never seen). However, I checked many places and the average rate is above $200 which is too much for this property unless the rooms undergo a major renovation (none scheduled that I know of).First of all, arriving at night in a rental car, the signage for the hotel is poor. Gold lettering on a brown stone wall is partially obscured by a tree for the small alley-width road leading to the hotel. The best direction is to head straight for the Normandie hotel which is clearly visible in front of you, and the Hilton is to your right. Check-in is conveniently located just off a circular driveway where you can park temporarily without a hassle. Valet parking is also readily available with plenty of personnel to shuttle the cars. No bell hop offered to get my bag or look after it. So, after check-in, I drove around the driveway and down the alley to their parking garage, a facility with in/out privileges at $10/day ($20/day valet). I ordered room service at 10:45pm which arrived within 45 minutes as they stated.The biggest nice surprise of the whole visit was that night when I had trouble enabling the in-room broadband, the hotel operator came up to personally fix it within five minutes. That鈥檚 five-star service.2/3 of the bottom level of the six-story garage is enclosed in a really tacky exhibition center where cheapo conferences take place. The days I was here, I saw temporary card tables set up with various wares such as cosmetics and crafts - dunno exactly what was going on. I mention this because the garage is small, so taking 2/3 of the first level for this purpose is questionable. After parking, I wheeled my luggage the medium far distance back to the hotel where my room was in the main building. The main building is a non-descript rectangular box aligned roughly perpendicular to the ocean. This allows most rooms on each side to have ocean views. Back in the 50's, when this box was constructed, the space on either side was not built up. Now, however, the fort side of the building, where my room was located, contains a large two-story ballroom building that extends a couple hundred feet out from the building. This means that all rooms on this side of the building overlook the roof of the ballroom area. In addition, as previously mentioned, the condo building construction continues which obscures yet more precious beachfront.My room was a plain, non-suite, which is typical of Hiltons all over the world. Nothing inside eludes of five-star luxury, nor does it have Motel 6 plainness. The AC unit is the old style wall mount with an updated digital thermostat. It chilled OK but did a so-so job of dehumidification that is typical of low-end AC units that do not have a separate dehumidify mode. The grill shows rust and corrosion, as does the door closer to the hallway. The bathroom has mold on the caulk line of the tub. The bathroom phone did not have dialtone, and the toilet does not shut off completely.I used the health club one afternoon. Machines include 6 treadmills (one down for service), one elliptical, one or two star steppers, a dozen or so resistance machines, and two or three free-weight positions. The club is part of the spa complex that includes the spa facility and a small cafe with tennis courts behind. The club is a simple, beautiful design with a roof sloping upward to the ocean side that is a wall of windows with the $1M view. The opposite and side walls have mirrors reflecting theocean view. TV's are placed too high to be viewable from the treadmills, but I found the ocean view to be preferable to watching CNN. The attendant provides towel service, and there are small lockers you can use (no locker room or showers that I could see, though). Resistance machines show wear on the fabric that needs to be replaced.I swam in the pool one morning at 7am (didn't realize the pool actually opens at 8am). Security saw me but didn't bother me. The main pool is 4ft deep and suitable for swimming laps only if you arrive in the very early a.m. Otherwise, as in all hotel pools everywhere, screaming kids rule until the pool closes in the evening. Additional pools ofvarying depths are interconnected, and there's a swim-up bar in the uppermost pool. The adjoining area provides plenty of choices for relaxing. Lounges with freshly cleaned cushions were already in place at 7am, as were the beach towels. You can choose from shady spots in the palm tree area or sunny spots along the beach. As the sun sets, the sand beach area is shaded. Speaking of the beach, many reviewers complainabout it but the bottom line for me is that for this area of San Juan, it's of pretty decent size and and well maintained (in comparison to the Normandie or Wyndham for example which are nearby and I also checked out).I checked out but did not use the beach locker room area which is conveniently located off the beach area on the bottom level of the hotel. The ceiling height is low here. The facility was clean but I didn't get a good feeling about leaving items in a locker there (you can padlock it). I'd recommend keeping your personal items with you or with a friend while you're in the pool.You won't see many young adults or beautiful people sunbathing here. In general, the guests I saw were late 30's to senior citizens, of medium to overweight but not obese build. Most women are conservative with their swimwear here which probably also goes along with the older clientele.I asked for some advice from the concierge and the travel desk, both of which are located off the open-air lobby.The travel desk was not helpful when I wanted to go on a tour Monday at 9:30am. I asked about the rain forest and was told I missed the only tour for the day, and that the cave tours only occur Wednesday-Sunday (maybe through their pre-arranged hotel pickup that's probably true but it's really external companies who do the tours and she could have called around or asked). She gave me incorrect directions to the rain forest (the road to the rain forest did NOT intersect the main highway). She did not offer any suggestions to explore this beautiful country and was not a person with the right attitude to be working in that position at the hotel.From the concierge, I asked for a recommendation for an off-site restaurant such as a pancake house that is breakfast-oriented. She said there are no pancake houses in Puerto Rico, and recommended the hotel restaurant that I said I'd been to but was tired of. I did end up eating there again for their $20 breakfast buffet which costs approximately the same as if you order pancakes, sausage, and eggs ala carte (drink not included). I went back to the concierge another morning and the guy was reading the paper and engaged in a conversation with another hotel employee who was sitting there. He did notice me and gave me the map I requested. A rack of literature was located next to this desk, all of which were the standard fare that tour companies and shopping centers give to the hotels for free).I ate in the main restaurant several times (breakfast x2, dinner x1, sunday brunch). The dining room is pleasant with windows facing the pool and ocean; you can also eat outside. Sunday brunch was the biggest rip-off at $30. It's similar to the breakfast buffet but offers carved meats (which were gone and not replenished during my meal), and some seafood. During the brunch, ordering off the menu is not offered. Many kids were running around free in the restaurant area (just like at Old Country Buffet in the states if anyone has ever been there). Young kids eat free, and older ones get a discount. At the breakfast brunch one morning, I walked up to the cook and asked for a freshly made omelet to order that he made no problem. However, I don't know if this was a protocol violation as this was the place where waiters placed their orders with the cooks. Steam table eggs were readily available as were a good variety of all the normal breakfast items.Checkout was speedy. I did ask about the $8.75/day resort fee that was added to my bill, and they told me it was part of the room fee.Pluses- nice health club, nice view with wall of windows overlooking the ocean. This is such a pleasantchange from the average hotel club which is located in the basement or another room without windows- beautiful pool area, clean, inviting- pretty beachfront (for the area). Hotels and condos swallow up most of the land here and this one has one of the nicer maintained private beach areas - not huge, though- Louisa the hotel operator, who at 11pm my first nights stay diagnosed a problem with the hotel broadband and personally brought and installed an Ethernet cable within five minutes of me talking with her - Brava!- late-night room service- convenient distance to airportMinuses- $15/night for in-room broadband, free at most business-class hotels these days- $5/15 minutes for wireless broadband in the lobby area, free at most business-class hotels these days- no mini-fridge, standard at most business class hotels these days. They will deliver one subjectto availability if you ask, though.- business lounge is tiny (3-4 tables), and free continental breakfast is just pastries no hot items- no restaurants within walking distance- bell hops where are you? Front desk didn't ask if I needed baggage assistance at check-in.- parking garage is too small (and will get worse as the condos next door start getting occupants)- breakfast buffet is approximately $20, pancakes with meat $10, $18 if you want eggs, too. drink notincluded.- hotel signage difficult to see from the road - hotel entrance road is tiny. banning parking on itwould be a good idea to make two-way passage easier- as in many tired, aging Hiltons worldwide, minor room issues: rusty grill on AC unit and door closer, mold along tub line, bathroom phone no dial tone, leaky toilet, mold/cleaning fluid smell from carpet- no HBO on room TV, just basic cable channels- beware of the bottle of water in your room. Hhonors members will think this is the free bottle you get at most Hiltons. However, this bottle costs you $7 charged to your room- sunday lunch buffet costs $30. Same basic buffet sans carved meats costs $15 nightly. Drink not included.- $8.75/day resort fee added to room charge. I inquired about this and they said it's part of the hotel fee and can't be deleted. This wasn't advertised when I reserved my room.- $1/day kids charity fee added to room charge (can be deleted)- 2/3 of the bottom story of the parking garage converted to an enclosed exhibition center where low-budget functions take place (indivduals renting booths setting up their card tables to hawk their goods and services). Tacky not Hilton caliber.- karaoke lady singing almost every night in the open lounge bar area, often until 3am or more (party went to 5am one night I was there). She is OK quality, but ofa caliber you'd expect to hear in a Holiday Inn off the interstate not in a five-star Carribbean resort.A small live band with island music would be nice.- expensive restaurants, and too many of them (seven). Most of the restaurants have extremely low occupancy (spa cafe, spanish restaurant, Italian? restaurant). Converting one to an enclosed SportsBar might be nice.- beware of the bottle of water in your room. Hhonors members will think this is the free bottle you get at most Hiltons. However, this bottle costs you $7 charged to your room- sunday lunch buffet costs $30. Same basic buffet sans carved meats costs $15 nightly. Drink not included.Speaking of that condo project Paseo Caribe next door...- Part of the site was owned by the Navy, and another was an outdoor parking lot owned by the Hilton(shame on the Navy for selling it vs. leaving it as a national park with the historic 1500's fort whichof course they are leaving intact)- It's not just a condo project; they anticipate a whole shopping complex with movie theaters, casino, etc.- The condos will invite more transient residents. Owners are not anticipated to live there- Guess who will be managing the timeshare condo arrangements? The HILTON.- So in fact, rich investors are using the condo as an investment and revenue source vs. as a residence and the Hilton is using the property as a hotel within a hotel (their words). They get a nice, new property to manage without spending all the capital (wonder if they will pump some of that back into renovating the 1950's main hotel building)?- Scheduled for completion in August, 2004, as of this writing, the building is still aconcrete shell, and they now anticipate a phased approach stretching out fully into 2005. 
